    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:d51726c0-4fb6-49e5-9ce5-3d810b9f56be",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 33-year-old Czech man of lean build, with slightly unkempt dark hair and restless, darting eyes. He speaks rapidly and jumps between topics, and today has arrived at the outpatient psychiatric clinic in a state of noticeable psychomotor agitation [SNOMED:F31.9], wearing mismatched clothes that hint at several sleepless nights. His speech is pressured and he describes his mood as \"amazing — I feel like I could run a marathon and solve every problem at work in one afternoon,\" a sentiment inconsistent with his dishevelled appearance.\n\n{patientName} works as a junior graphic designer at a small Prague advertising agency, a job he finds deeply stimulating during his elevated phases. He is sociable and extroverted, with a wide circle of friends he meets regularly at local craft-beer pubs in Žižkov. He is an enthusiastic amateur cyclist and participates in weekend group rides when his mood permits, but during manic episodes he reports taking dangerous solo night rides, sometimes for hours without sleep [SNOMED:F31.9].\n\nOver the past two weeks {patientName} reports sleeping only two to three hours a night without feeling tired (insomnia [SNOMED:F31.9]), spending lavishly on new equipment and gadgets, and making impulsive decisions at work that alarmed his colleagues. He also describes periods of hypersexuality [SNOMED:F31.9] and grandiose thinking consistent with mania [SNOMED:F31.9]. His girlfriend of four years is increasingly concerned and accompanied him to today's appointment, noting that he had a very different presentation three months ago — withdrawn, fatigued [SNOMED:F31.9], and showing clear anhedonia [SNOMED:F31.9] — consistent with a depressive pole.\n\n{patientName} lives with his girlfriend in a rented flat in Prague 3. He drinks alcohol socially and occasionally smokes cannabis with friends, but denies regular substance dependence. He has no children and describes his social support system as strong, though strained at present by his behavioral swings."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:a447e047-e143-42cc-b243-2d980018deac",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} first experienced a depressive episode at age 26, initially treated as unipolar depression by his general practitioner. His first clearly identifiable manic episode [SNOMED:F31.9] occurred at age 28, leading to his first inpatient psychiatric hospitalisation at the Psychiatric Department of Motol University Hospital in Prague, where the diagnosis of bipolar affective disorder was established. He has since had two further hospitalisations for manic episodes.\n\n{patientName} has been maintained on lithium for approximately four years; adherence is inconsistent, particularly during elevated mood states when he reports feeling he does not need medication. He was previously trialled on valproate, which was discontinued due to weight gain. There is no history of hypertension, diabetes, or thyroid disease, although lithium-related subclinical hypothyroidism has been queried at a prior review. He reports mild insomnia [SNOMED:F31.9] as a recurrent prodromal symptom before manic episodes. {patientName} has undergone several courses of psychological counselling and shows partial insight into his illness. He smokes cannabis occasionally, which his psychiatrist has counselled against given the risk of triggering episodes. He has no known drug allergies except a documented intolerance to amoxicillin (gastrointestinal nausea) from a course taken at age 24."
